  "text": "## HTTP Filter Factory Registration and Instantiation in Envoy v1.31.2\n\nThe HTTP filter factory system in Envoy follows a two-stage model: static registration at initialization and per-connection instantiation at runtime.\n\n### 1. Filter Factory Registry and Registration\n\n**Core Interface** (envoy/server/filter_config.h):\n- `NamedHttpFilterConfigFactory` - Base interface for HTTP filter factories. Each HTTP filter implements a config factory that extends this interface.\n- `UpstreamHttpFilterConfigFactory` - Parallel interface for upstream-specific HTTP filters.\n\nFilters are registered statically using `Registry::RegisterFactory<FilterConfigType, NamedHttpFilterConfigFactory>()`. The registry (Registry::FactoryRegistry<NamedHttpFilterConfigFactory>) stores factories indexed by their type name.\n\n### 2. Factory Callback and Filter Instantiation\n\n**Core Types** (envoy/http/filter_factory.h):\n- `FilterFactoryCb` - Function type `std::function<void(FilterChainFactoryCallbacks&)>` that creates and installs filters for a stream. Factories return this callback during initialization.\n- `FilterChainManager` - Abstract interface with `applyFilterFactoryCb()` method, implemented per-connection to manage filter instantiation.\n- `FilterChainFactory` - Interface for creating filter chains, with `createFilterChain()` called when new streams arrive.\n\n### 3. Configuration and Filter Chain Creation\n\n**Configuration Processing** (source/extensions/filters/network/http_connection_manager/config.h and config.cc):\n- `HttpConnectionManagerConfig` implements `Http::FilterChainFactory`.\n- During construction, it uses `FilterChainHelper::processFilters()` (source/common/http/filter_chain_helper.h) to process the HTTP filters configuration.\n- `processFilters()` iterates through each filter in the config and:\n  - Retrieves the factory from the registry using `Config::Utility::getAndCheckFactory<>`\n  - Creates a `FilterConfigProvider` using `filter_config_provider_manager_.createStaticFilterConfigProvider()`\n  - For dynamic filters, creates `HttpDynamicFilterConfigProviderImpl` (source/common/filter/config_discovery_impl.h) which manages runtime filter config updates\n\n**Key Data Structure** (source/common/filter/config_discovery_impl.h line 185-189):\n```cpp\nstruct NamedHttpFilterFactoryCb {\n  std::string name;                    // Canonical filter name\n  Http::FilterFactoryCb factory_cb;   // Factory function\n};\n```\n\n### 4. Per-Connection Filter Chain Creation\n\n**Stream Creation** (source/common/http/filter_manager.h and filter_manager.cc):\n- `FilterManager` implements `FilterChainManager` and manages filters for a single stream.\n- When a new stream is created, `FilterManager::createFilterChain()` is called (line 1550).\n- This calls `filter_chain_factory_.createFilterChain(*this, false, options)` where the factory is the `HttpConnectionManagerConfig`.\n\n**Filter Chain Utility** (source/common/http/filter_chain_helper.cc line 17-47):\n- `FilterChainUtility::createFilterChainForFactories()` iterates through the pre-configured `FilterFactoriesList`.\n- For each filter config provider, it retrieves the current filter factory callback via `provider->config()`.\n- It calls `manager.applyFilterFactoryCb()` with the filter factory callback and filter context.\n\n**Per-Stream Filter Instantiation** (source/common/http/filter_manager.cc line 551-553):\n```cpp\nvoid FilterManager::applyFilterFactoryCb(FilterContext context, FilterFactoryCb& factory) {\n  FilterChainFactoryCallbacksImpl callbacks(*this, context);\n  factory(callbacks);\n}\n```\nThe factory callback is invoked with a `FilterChainFactoryCallbacksImpl` object that the factory uses to call `callbacks.addStreamFilter()`, `callbacks.addStreamDecoderFilter()`, etc., to instantiate actual filter objects.\n\n### 5. Dynamic Filter Configuration\n\n**Runtime Updates** (source/common/filter/config_discovery_impl.h line 195-229):\n- `HttpDynamicFilterConfigProviderImpl` manages filters that can be updated at runtime via xDS.\n- When a config update arrives, `instantiateFilterFactory()` is called (line 221-229):\n  - Looks up the factory in the registry using `Registry::FactoryRegistry<>::getFactoryByType()`\n  - Calls `factory->createFilterFactoryFromProto()` with the new config\n  - Returns a `NamedHttpFilterFactoryCb` containing the filter name and updated factory callback\n\n### Summary Flow\n\n1. **Initialization**: `HttpConnectionManagerConfig` constructor processes HTTP filters config via `FilterChainHelper::processFilters()`, creating `FilterConfigProvider` instances that hold factory callbacks.\n\n2. **Stream Creation**: When a new HTTP stream is created, `FilterManager::createFilterChain()` is called.\n\n3. **Chain Assembly**: `FilterChainUtility::createFilterChainForFactories()` retrieves each filter's factory callback and calls `FilterManager::applyFilterFactoryCb()`.\n\n4. **Filter Instantiation**: The factory callback is invoked with `FilterChainFactoryCallbacksImpl`, which instantiates actual filter objects and adds them to the chain.\n\n5. **Dynamic Updates**: `HttpDynamicFilterConfigProviderImpl` handles xDS config changes by looking up factories in the registry and calling `instantiateFilterFactory()` to create new filter callbacks.\n\nThis design separates configuration processing (factory lookup) from per-connection instantiation, allowing efficient reuse of static factory configurations for each new stream."
}

